#compdef backdown
# ============================================================================
# backdown - interactive duplicate-file deduplicator
#             (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : Denys Séguret (Canop)
# Upstream: https://github.com/Canop/backdown
# crates : backdown (binary: backdown)
#
# `backdown` walks a directory tree, hashes every file
# with BLAKE3, groups files by identical content hash,
# and presents a TUI flow that lets the user pick which
# duplicates to remove. It supports image-only mode (for
# photo libraries) and emits a JSON report of the
# deduplication actions taken. Authored by Denys Séguret
# (Canop) - the author behind broot, bacon, lapin, and
# the broader bacon-family Rust TUI tooling.
#
# Usage:
#   backdown [-i] [path]
#
# Flags (argh):
#   -i, --only-images        - only consider image files
#                              (jpg, png, gif, webp, ...)
#                              when grouping duplicates
#   -v, --version            - print version
#   <path>                   - directory to scan
#                              (default: current dir)
#
# Operational flow:
#   1. Walk <path> and collect candidate files
#   2. Group by file size (quick pre-filter)
#   3. For each size-group with >1 file, hash each file
#      with BLAKE3 + group by hash
#   4. Present each hash-group of duplicates as an
#      interactive choice in the TUI
#   5. Apply user-selected removals + emit JSON action
#      report
#
# The blake3 lane is built on `blake3 = "1.4"` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported from src/hash.rs as `blake3::Hasher::new()`
# + `hasher.finalize()`), the canonical Rust BLAKE3
# implementation by the BLAKE3-team - github.com/BLAKE3-
# team/BLAKE3, 5700+ stars. The crate is the *reference
# implementation by the algorithm's own authors*:
#   - Jack O'Connor (Anchore)
#   - Jean-Philippe Aumasson (Kudelski Security)
#   - Samuel Neves (University of Coimbra)
#   - Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn (Electric Coin Company)
#
# BLAKE3 (2020) is the successor to BLAKE2 (2012), itself
# the SHA-3 finalist by Aumasson + Neves + Wilcox-O'Hearn
# + Henzen. The algorithm targets simultaneous SIMD
# throughput on modern CPUs + GPU parallelization +
# verified streaming via a Merkle tree (the `bao`
# verified-streaming tool, by the same author, uses
# BLAKE3's tree structure for incremental verification
# of large files). BLAKE3 is approximately 5x-10x faster
# than SHA-256 on the same hardware, while providing
# the same 256-bit collision resistance.
#
# The Rust `blake3` crate is the canonical reference -
# the same source code is the canonical implementation
# in the spec document. C / assembly variants exist as
# additional canonical implementations in the same
# repository (e.g. `c/blake3_avx512.c` for the AVX-512
# SIMD path), all governed under one umbrella by the
# original authors.
#
# backdown uses BLAKE3's streaming hasher (`Hasher::new()
# + io::copy(&mut file, &mut hasher) + hasher.finalize()`)
# to compute the per-file content hash. The streaming
# API lets backdown hash files of arbitrary size with
# O(BLOCK_SIZE) memory rather than reading the whole file
# into RAM first, which matters when dedup-scanning
# directories that may contain multi-gigabyte files.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 245 :: BLAKE3 cryptographic hashing (SIMD-parallel
#              + tree-structured + verified-streaming)
# Round 1433 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 245
#                                   (round-300 landmark)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3 (`blake3` crate)
#                                       - the reference
#                                         implementation
#                                         by the
#                                         algorithm's
#                                         own authors
#                                         (O'Connor +
#                                         Aumasson +
#                                         Neves +
#                                         Wilcox-O'Hearn)
#   Go      : zeebo/blake3              - the de-facto
#                                         Go BLAKE3
#                                         implementation
#                                         by Jeff Wendling
#                                         (Storj founding
#                                         engineer);
#                                         hand-tuned AVX2
#                                         + ARM NEON
#                                         assembly paths
#   TS/Node : @node-rs/blake3            - napi-rs Node
#                                         binding wrapping
#                                         the RustCrypto
#                                         blake3 crate
#                                         (which is itself
#                                         a separate-from-
#                                         BLAKE3-team
#                                         pure-Rust impl
#                                         under the
#                                         RustCrypto
#                                         umbrella)
#
# BLAKE3 is a clean spec-bound axis - the BLAKE3 paper +
# the BLAKE3-team reference C / assembly / Rust code
# define the algorithm + test vectors byte-for-byte.
# Compliant implementations produce bit-identical hashes
# for the same input across all three lanes.
#
# Structural commentary:
#   - BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3 (Rust): root-of-trust where
#     library-author = algorithm-author; multi-implementation
#     repo with C, assembly, and Rust paths governed under
#     one umbrella
#   - zeebo/blake3 (Go): hand-tuned assembly paths for
#     AVX2 + ARM NEON; Jeff Wendling is the same author
#     behind much of Storj's content-addressed storage
#     infrastructure, so the library is battle-tested
#     against multi-PB workloads
#   - @node-rs/blake3 (Node): napi-rs binding to
#     RustCrypto/blake3 (a separate pure-Rust impl from
#     the BLAKE3-team reference, governed by the
#     RustCrypto umbrella); the Node binding inherits
#     the napi-rs cross-platform + zero-runtime-overhead
#     guarantees
#
# Interesting cross-language observation: BLAKE3's Rust
# slot has *two* canonical Rust libraries - the BLAKE3-
# team/BLAKE3 reference crate AND the RustCrypto/blake3
# crate. The latter exists because the RustCrypto umbrella
# wanted BLAKE3 to fit into the same `Digest` trait
# ecosystem as their SHA-2 / SHA-3 / Keccak etc. crates.
# Both are spec-compliant; @node-rs/blake3 binds to the
# RustCrypto variant because of the trait ecosystem fit.
#
# Cross-language interop at the hash-output level - 32
# bytes of BLAKE3 hash from any of the three lanes is
# byte-identical for the same input.
#
# Axis 245 opens at the round-300 landmark R1433 with the
# Rust slot at the canonical authors-of-the-algorithm
# reference implementation.
# ============================================================================

_backdown() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-i --only-images)'{-i,--only-images}'[only consider image files when grouping]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1:directory to scan:_files -/'
}

_backdown "$@"
